 animals through riddling forms or enigmatic language, balancing an attempt to speak and listen to things with an understanding that these nonhumans often elude, defy and withdraw from us. But the active role that things have in the early medieval world is also linked to the Germanic origins of the word, where a þing is a kind of assembly, with the ability to draw together other elements, creating assemblages in which human and nonhuman forces combine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArts in general. 0aCivilization, Anglo-Saxon. 0aEnglish literatureyOld English, ca. 450-1100xHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature (General). 0aMaterial culturezGreat BritainxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aLiterature Studies 2021. 4aMedieval Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Saxon.  aagency.  aanimate.  ainanimate.  anonhuman.  ariddles.  athings.  avoice.1 aPaz, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526115997zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526115997/original  a978-3-11-128281-7 Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA